{"recorded_at":"2026-03-08T23:43:13.667329Z","type":"assistant_message_complete","session_id":"sess_500c23b7a331b599cb22dc29963ca67e","turn":1,"message":{"id":"msg_dc3858311609b13a","role":"assistant","created_at":"2026-03-08T23:43:13.657814Z","content":[{"type":"text","text":{"text":"Recent experiments with “optical metasurfaces” showed that engineers can create flat, paper-thin lenses that dynamically switch between focusing and defocusing light by applying a low voltage. This tunable behavior comes from nanoscale pillars that reorient within a flexible polymer layer, hinting at future ultra-light imaging systems without moving parts.\n\nOn the microbiology front, scientists found that certain soil bacteria can enter a metabolically active “half-sleep” state when water is scarce—maintaining essential DNA repair and protein turnover while suspending growth. This intermediate state helps them survive drought conditions yet lets them resume full activity much faster once moisture returns."}}]}}
{"recorded_at":"2026-03-08T23:43:13.670594Z","type":"assistant_message_persisted","session_id":"sess_500c23b7a331b599cb22dc29963ca67e","turn":1,"message":{"id":"msg_dc3858311609b13a","role":"assistant","created_at":"2026-03-08T23:43:13.657814Z","content":[{"type":"text","text":{"text":"Recent experiments with “optical metasurfaces” showed that engineers can create flat, paper-thin lenses that dynamically switch between focusing and defocusing light by applying a low voltage. This tunable behavior comes from nanoscale pillars that reorient within a flexible polymer layer, hinting at future ultra-light imaging systems without moving parts.\n\nOn the microbiology front, scientists found that certain soil bacteria can enter a metabolically active “half-sleep” state when water is scarce—maintaining essential DNA repair and protein turnover while suspending growth. This intermediate state helps them survive drought conditions yet lets them resume full activity much faster once moisture returns."}}]}}
{"recorded_at":"2026-03-08T23:43:13.671434Z","type":"run_completed","session_id":"sess_500c23b7a331b599cb22dc29963ca67e","result":{"status":"completed","session":{"id":"sess_500c23b7a331b599cb22dc29963ca67e","name":"tell me something new","working_dir":"/Users/rex/projects/goose-go","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5-codex","type":"terminal","created_at":1773013374,"updated_at":1773013393,"message_count":6,"conversation":{"messages":[{"id":"msg_6ca349a1ce598838","role":"user","created_at":"2026-03-08T23:42:54.327452Z","content":[{"type":"text","text":{"text":"tell me something new"}}]},{"id":"msg_9d215102c56797fe","role":"assistant","created_at":"2026-03-08T23:42:55.702916Z","content":[{"type":"text","text":{"text":"Here’s something you might not know: researchers recently demonstrated that certain bioluminescent fungi can alter the timing of their glow based on fungal circadian rhythms. This suggests that fungi, like plants and animals, use internal clocks to regulate metabolic processes—raising fresh questions about how non-animal organisms keep time."}}]},{"id":"msg_596005c0ac01f12d","role":"user","created_at":"2026-03-08T23:43:04.700205Z","content":[{"type":"text","text":{"text":"more of this"}}]},{"id":"msg_d5e10b422e709230","role":"assistant","created_at":"2026-03-08T23:43:05.910892Z","content":[{"type":"text","text":{"text":"Researchers studying marine biology recently discovered that some deep-sea squids can modulate the polarization of their skin’s reflective cells, not just their brightness or color. By twisting plate-like structures called chromatophores, these squids can control the orientation of light waves—a potential form of communication invisible to most predators."}}]},{"id":"msg_34c6002c0163773e","role":"user","created_at":"2026-03-08T23:43:11.99976Z","content":[{"type":"text","text":{"text":"tell me something new"}}]},{"id":"msg_dc3858311609b13a","role":"assistant","created_at":"2026-03-08T23:43:13.657814Z","content":[{"type":"text","text":{"text":"Recent experiments with “optical metasurfaces” showed that engineers can create flat, paper-thin lenses that dynamically switch between focusing and defocusing light by applying a low voltage. This tunable behavior comes from nanoscale pillars that reorient within a flexible polymer layer, hinting at future ultra-light imaging systems without moving parts.\n\nOn the microbiology front, scientists found that certain soil bacteria can enter a metabolically active “half-sleep” state when water is scarce—maintaining essential DNA repair and protein turnover while suspending growth. This intermediate state helps them survive drought conditions yet lets them resume full activity much faster once moisture returns."}}]}]}},"turns":1}}
